english:
  title: A Letter Presented to Scholar Lee on the Matter of Recognizing Talent
  author: Lim Chun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On this day, I, Lim, humbly bow and prostrate myself before you, honored official.

    Consider the legendary blades Mokya and Ganjiang—the supreme treasures of all under Heaven. Yet they lay buried in the earth of Yejang and Pungsung, their purple radiance piercing the space between the Plow and Bull constellations, unknown to any soul. Only when Lei Huan ascended the tower and gazed upward did he discern their presence. Then, unearthing them and polishing them with the soil of Nanchang, their brilliance blazed forth so dazzling that all who beheld them were struck with wonder. Had Huan possessed no such insight, those divine instruments wrought by Heaven would have remained forever buried, perhaps never to grace the world with their splendor.

    I have languished long in this remote and frozen valley. Though my anguished spirit rises toward Heaven itself, there is no Lei Huan in this world to perceive it, to draw forth its radiance. How lamentable this is! Therefore I dare to fashion these humble and scattered words to lay before you. I beseech you to grant them your scrutiny.

    Once I received the hundred-fold tempered essence of steel in the furnaces of creation itself. Yin and yang formed my substance; the five elements composed my being; the twenty-eight mansions of stars adorned my breast. Thus endowed with spirit, I was born to benefit all things. I took virtue and righteousness as my hilt and blade, wisdom and courage as my edge. I clothed myself in the steadfastness of word and deed, adorned myself with the brilliance of learning and eloquence. Sheathed and guarded thus, I preserved myself in clarity and wisdom. Wielded and employed, I could meet any moment and fulfill my purpose. Honed upon the whetstone of reputation and honor, refined by the discipline of study, I could cleave the floating clouds above and sever the very axis of earth below. Raised, I met no obstacle; swung, I encountered no resistance. Within Heaven and Earth I could move freely without hindrance.

    Yet for any instrument of extraordinary capability, there must arise an extraordinary person to accomplish extraordinary deeds. Thus dust obscures my gleam, soil corrodes my patterns, my lustrous finish peels away like a serpent's shed skin, and I have kept company with rusted iron for ages untold. Yet still my spirit and strange brilliance burn forth amid grass and stone, impossible to conceal—still potent enough to command spirits, summon thunder and lightning, and stir the very stars.

    Alas! Did Heaven forge this thing merely to leave it buried in darkness, hidden and unexpressed, ultimately lost and abandoned? No!

    I have observed that your capaciousness of mind is boundless, your natural endowments splendid and great. Combined with your keen discernment and far-reaching wisdom, versed as you are in all things, you have risen to high station and wielded great authority. You delight in virtue and transcend the snares of power; you welcome heroes and men of excellence. Thus all the worthy scholars under Heaven desire to serve you, all seek to establish their names and worth in your presence. You are truly the great craftsman of our age.

    Therefore, let all the blades—Dragon Spring, Great Awe, Deepwater Verdure, Mighty Lord—all such treasures be gathered and preserved as the jewels of your arsenal. Yet this is not merely that you might slay rhinoceros and tiger in the manner of common men. Rather, it is that you might sweep away treachery and corruption, cleanse the realm of all discord, command the Son of Heaven to lead the princes, and bring all Four Seas into submission and peace.

    If you would but wipe clear the eyes of Lei Huan and gaze upon the radiance between Plow and Bull, excavate the treasure and draw it forth, scrape away its tarnish and polish its gleam—then in one day its substance shall be revealed, in two days its brilliance shall shine, and on the third day its true visage shall be beheld. Then its service in your employ shall know no bounds, its utility far exceeding the single cut of a blunted blade.

    Should you abandon me in this frozen valley to become an object of uselessness, I shall take flight to escape the calamity of the arsenal, or plunge into the waters of Pingzin to slumber until the proper time and proper person arise. Then what enlightened craftsman or sage would not seek to recover such a rare and precious thing?

    I tremble with awe at my presumption. I bow twice in reverence.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Lei Huan (雷煥) and the swords Mokya and Ganjiang are references to a famous tale from Chinese legend about the discovery of legendary blades buried underground, their discovery enabled by Lei Huan's observation of celestial signs.
  - key: ''
    value: The Plow and Bull (斗牛) refer to constellations in Chinese astronomy.
  - key: ''
    value: The Dragon Spring, Great Awe, Deepwater Verdure, and Mighty Lord are all names of legendary swords in Chinese tradition.
  - key: ''
    value: This memorial employs the extended metaphor of a legendary sword awaiting recognition by a worthy person—a conventional form for Korean literati seeking patronage or recognition from powerful officials.
